# Parallel e2e Execution

## Context

Today's e2e suite runs strictly sequentially. `run_e2e.sh` walks 64
invocations (15 fixtures x 2 trigger modes + 4 negatives) one-at-a-time,
~60 min wall-clock on a multicore host. The test substrate is already
parallelism-safe:

- Every shell driver (`roundtrip_e2e.sh`, `rt_shared_mem.sh`, the four
  negative drivers) uses `mktemp` for state files in `/tmp` and `/dev/shm`
  (Tier-1: `roundtrip_e2e.sh:78-81`; Tier-2: `rt_shared_mem.sh:66`). No
  fixed paths.
- `pick_free_port()` in `hybrid_vsim/src/hybrid/qemu_handback.hpp:41-63`
  asks the kernel for an ephemeral gdbstub port per spawn. Zero collision
  risk.
- No global locks, no fixed `/tmp` paths, no shared lockfiles.
- CTest registration in `cmake/HybridConfig.cmake` has no `RESOURCE_LOCK`
  or `PROCESSORS` hints. `ctest -j N` would already run in parallel today
  but lacks cost hints, so the long matmul cases can starve a slot at the
  tail of a `-j` schedule.

The bottleneck is purely the orchestration loop. Goal: cut wall time on a
multicore host without changing test semantics, fixture sources, or the
summary output users rely on.

## Approach

Two layers, independent:

1. **`run_e2e.sh`** -- replace the sequential mode/test nested loops
   (`run_e2e.sh:103-144`) with a bounded bash job pool. Per-test
   stdout/stderr is captured to a per-job logfile and printed atomically
   when the job finishes; the user sees clean per-test blocks instead of
   interleaved noise from N concurrent QEMUs. Default
   `JOBS="${JOBS:-$(nproc)}"`, clamped by a `/dev/shm` headroom check.
   Negative tests stay serial -- 4 quick rc-checks where parallelism
   gives nothing, and `rt_pty_handback` is the trickiest of the bunch.

2. **CTest** -- annotate registrations in `cmake/HybridConfig.cmake` so
   `ctest -j N -L hybrid-e2e` is a first-class parallel entrypoint, with
   `COST` set so long matmul variants get scheduled first (CTest greedily
   schedules highest-cost first to minimize tail).

### Resource budget

Per parallel slot (peak):
- 3 concurrent processes: QEMU 1, vsim, QEMU 2
- ~128 MB `/dev/shm` mmap for Tier-2 (`mktemp -p /dev/shm` + `truncate`
  in `rt_shared_mem.sh`)
- ~1 vCPU saturating during vsim compute or QEMU 2 boot
- ephemeral gdbstub TCP port (kernel-assigned)

Default cap: `JOBS = min(nproc, free_shm_mb / 256)` -- 256 MB headroom
per slot leaves margin for the Tier-2 backing file plus QEMU's own
scratch. Document the heuristic in the script header.

### `run_e2e.sh` shape

Refactor the existing nested loops into:

- `RT_TESTS`, `NEG_TESTS` arrays: unchanged.
- One function `run_one "$mode" "$entry"` doing what the inner loop body
  does today, redirecting all output to `$LOG_DIR/$mode--$fixture.log`.
  On exit, the function emits one atomic line via `flock`-protected
  append to `$RESULTS_FILE`:
  `[i/N] PASS|FAIL mode=csr fixture=rt_pc_jump elapsed=12s`.
- A bash semaphore via FIFO + N tokens caps concurrency at `$JOBS`. Each
  job reads a token before running, writes it back on exit. Standard
  pattern; avoids xargs argv-quoting pitfalls and lets us redirect cleanly.
- After all background jobs `wait`, the 4 negative tests run serially in
  the same `run_one` shape (mode label `neg`).
- Counters (`csr_pass`, `pc_pass`, `csr_fail`, ...) live in a counters
  file appended under `flock` by each child. Final summary line is
  unchanged from today's
  `csr Np/Mf/Os  pc Np/Mf/Os  neg Np/Mf/Os  total X PASS|FAIL`.

Progress emission: each job ends with one line printed to the controlling
TTY (atomic single-write under `flock`). Successful tests get only the
one-liner; failed tests additionally have their full log streamed at end,
in deterministic order (csr-mode in array order, then pc-mode, then neg).
Successful logs are kept in `$LOG_DIR` and noted in the summary so the
user can grep them without re-running.

### CTest hints (`hybrid_vsim/cmake/HybridConfig.cmake`)

- All Tier-1 registrations (csr + pc): `set_tests_properties(... PROPERTIES COST 30)`.
- All Tier-2 registrations except matmul: `COST 60`.
- `rt_c_matmul` csr + pc variants: `COST 120` (matches the existing
  per-fixture timeout extension in `run_e2e.sh`).
- Negative tests: untouched.

CTest schedules highest-cost tests first under `-j`, so matmul starts
immediately and isn't left as a long tail. No `RESOURCE_LOCK` is needed
-- the substrate is already isolated.

